            <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
            <p class="section-intro">Find answers to common questions about pursuing a career in embedded systems:</p>
            
            <div class="accordion">
                <div class="accordion-item active">
                    <div class="accordion-header">What educational background is needed for embedded systems?</div>
                    <div class="accordion-content">
                        <p>A bachelor's degree in Electrical Engineering, Computer Engineering, or Computer Science provides a solid foundation. However, specific knowledge in microcontrollers, digital electronics, programming (especially C/C++), and computer architecture is essential. Many professionals also pursue specialized master's degrees or certifications in embedded systems to enhance their expertise.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="accordion-item">
                    <div class="accordion-header">How is embedded systems different from general software development?</div>
                    <div class="accordion-content">
                        <p>Embedded systems development differs from general software development in several key ways:</p>
                        <p>• It involves programming for resource-constrained devices with limited memory and processing power</p>
                        <p>• It requires understanding of hardware-software interaction and low-level programming</p>
                        <p>• It often involves real-time constraints where timing is critical</p>
                        <p>• It typically uses languages like C/C++ rather than higher-level languages</p>
                        <p>• It requires consideration of power consumption, reliability, and safety requirements</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="accordion-item">
                    <div class="accordion-header">What programming languages are most important for embedded systems?</div>
                    <div class="accordion-content">
                        <p>C is the most widely used language in embedded systems due to its efficiency, low-level capabilities, and direct hardware control. C++ is increasingly popular for more complex systems. Assembly language is still important for performance-critical sections and low-level hardware interaction. Other languages gaining traction include:</p>
                        <p>• Rust: For memory-safe systems programming</p>
                        <p>• Python: For rapid prototyping and with MicroPython for microcontrollers</p>
                        <p>• Ada: For safety-critical applications</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="accordion-item">
                    <div class="accordion-header">How do I start learning embedded systems as a beginner?</div>
                    <div class="accordion-content">
                        <p>For beginners, a structured approach to learning embedded systems includes:</p>
                        <p>1. Start with Arduino or similar beginner-friendly platforms to understand basic concepts</p>
                        <p>2. Learn C programming fundamentals, focusing on pointers, memory management, and bit manipulation</p>
                        <p>3. Study digital electronics and microcontroller architecture basics</p>
                        <p>4. Progress to more professional development boards like STM32, ESP32, or Raspberry Pi Pico</p>
                        <p>5. Learn to read datasheets and technical documentation</p>
                        <p>6. Practice with small projects that integrate sensors, actuators, and communication interfaces</p>
                        <p>7. Explore real-time operating systems like FreeRTOS</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="accordion-item">
                    <div class="accordion-header">What are the growth prospects in embedded systems?</div>
                    <div class="accordion-content">
                        <p>The embedded systems field offers excellent growth prospects due to the proliferation of IoT devices, smart appliances, automotive electronics, and industrial automation. Career progression typically moves from junior embedded engineer to senior roles, then to specialized positions like RTOS specialist, embedded security expert, or IoT architect. Many professionals also move into technical leadership, systems architecture, or product management roles. With the integration of AI and edge computing into embedded systems, professionals with skills in these areas are particularly in demand.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
